            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to cast into hell",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rather, into Gehenna. It is a deep misfortune that our English Version has made no consistent difference of rendering between ‘the place of the dead,’ ‘the intermediate state between death and resurrection’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "(Hades, Sheol),",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Gehenna, which is sometimes metaphorically used (as here) for a place of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "punishment",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " after death. Gehenna was a purely Hebrew word, and corresponded primarily to purely Hebrew conceptions. Our Lord (if He spoke Greek) did not attempt to represent it by any analogous, but imperfectly equivalent, Greek term like Tartarus (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and certainly the Apostles and Evangelists did not. They simply ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "transliterated",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Hebrew term (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "גי הנם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Gê Hinnom, Valley of Hinnom) into Greek letters. It is surely a plain positive duty to follow so clear an example, and not to render Gehenna by English terms which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cannot",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " connote ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "exactly",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the same conceptions. The Valley of Hinnom, or of the Sons of Hinnom (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
